I'm willing to change my mind if I see such evidence. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 304<br> <font color=#333333>(6/17/04 5:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2705.topic&index=153>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> More food for thought:<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.diplomatsforchange.com/index.html">Diplomats for Change</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->  read it.  People who have devoted their lives to the foreign service, many of whom are former 4 star generals or Republican appointees, who think the Bush administration's foreign policy has been a disaster.  <br>
<br>
And Bush is spending his time today refuting the conclusions of the bi-partisan 9/11 commission that there was a link between Hussein and Al Qaeda.  His evidence to oppose months of work and thousands of man hours of research and testimony?  El-zippo. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lehammer8>Lehammer8</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 380<br> <font color=#333333>(6/18/04 4:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2705.topic&index=154>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Look at the raw testimony yourself</span><hr size=1> www.9-11commission.gov<br>
<br>
I'm finding it useful to read the raw testimony of witnesses like Condoleeza Rice, Madeline Albright and Colin Powell and form my own opinions.  The witnesses are under oath, and thus are risking perjury charges if they flat-out lie.<br>
<br>
My preliminary opinions: there's an awful lot of Monday-morning quarterbacking going on, which is unfortunate.  Both the Clinton and Bush administrations have been strongly attacked.  Seems unjustified since hardly any of us in America saw counterrorism as a top priority before 9/11.  We the people must share the blame with our leaders for ignoring the evidence of a growing threat.  Many of the questioners imply that we should have invaded Afghanistan previous to 9/11, and I don't think national or world opinion would have tolerated it, from either Bush or Clinton.<br>
<br>
And there's been some political football such as the &quot;swatting flies&quot; question to Rice, obviously aimed at discrediting Bush in a sound-bite format, that detracts from the credibility of the commission's stated aim to learn the lessons, not place the blame.<br>
<br>
However, it is clearly evident from testimony that the Bush administration pushed counterrorism further to the back burner.  And equally clear is a powerful effort to hide evidence of this, and evidence of weak administration responses to the threat info being reported in the summer of 2001.  <br>
<br>
Examples include efforts to keep Condoleeza Rice from testifying, especially in public.  Also keeping classified crucial documents like the August 6, 2001 Presidential Daily Briefing memo entitled &quot;Bin Laden Determined to Attack Inside the United States&quot;.  <br>
<br>
Rice says there was no new threat info in this document, but we the public can't judge that for ourselves unless its declassified.  The commission itself has had limited access to this memo, and at least one doesn't share Rice's opinion.<br>
<br>
Again, I think 9/11 caught us all napping.  Its hardly fair to point at Bush and say &quot;You were asleep at the wheel&quot;... we all were.<br>
<br>
But its hardly strong leadership to blame everyone else then hide the evidence of your own culpability.<br>
<br>
My idea of strong leadership after 9/11 would have been to apologize for not preventing the attacks, then to move powerfully to destroy Al-Qaida and undermine its ideology.  But the lion's share of our effort has gone to attacking Iraq instead.  And our President lied to us about why.<br>
<br>
He's still telling us that Al-Qaida and Iraq were linked.  His evidence: they met.  No evidence showing Saddam funded, worked with, or assisted Al-Qaida in any way, and certainly not with 9/11... even Bush now admits no direct connection with 9/11, though he certainly implied the opposite in the run-up to invasion.<br>
<br>
Stronger evidence links Al-Qaida to Sudan, Iran, Saudi Arabia and of course Afghanistan.  The evidence linking Iraq is pathetically weak by comparison, yet Bush still clings to it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=smawty>smawty</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#333333>(6/18/04 10:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2705.topic&index=155>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> .</span><hr size=1> None of this matters in the context of the election.  Kerry supported the war.  Kerry voted for the war.  Kerry said Saddam had WMDs.  Kerry said Iraq was a threat.  Kerry doesn't want to retreat.  The only difference is Bush did what he thought was the best for America but Kerry did what the polls said he should do.  So unless you are trying to convince people to vote for Nader or you are a terrorist sympathizer/blame America first liberal then why waste your breath? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 305<br> <font color=#333333>(6/18/04 10:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2705.topic&index=156>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Look at the raw testimony yourself</span><hr size=1> To be fair, Condoleeza Rice's refusal to testify had nothing to do with an attempt to deceive.  There is a well established doctrine of executive privilege, rooted firmly in maintaining this country's Constitutionally mandated separation of powers.  <br>
